        </div>
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-pdtf-navy mb-6">Building AI Agents for Property?</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600">
          AI agents are arriving in conveyancing — handling enquiries, chasing updates, reviewing documents, and managing cases. They need structured, verified data to work reliably. PDTF is that data layer.
        </p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-pdtf-navy mb-3">Structured by Default</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
            Every property data point is JSON Schema-validated with a known path. No scraping PDFs or parsing emails — your agent reads structured data directly.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-pdtf-navy mb-3">Verified Claims</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
            Every data element carries provenance: who said it, when, with what evidence, at what trust level. Your agent can make decisions based on verified facts, not assumptions.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-pdtf-navy mb-3">Role-Based Access</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
            PDTF's permission model means your agent only sees what it should. Confidentiality and access control are built into the framework, not bolted on.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="mt-8 text-center">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          If you're building property AI — whether for conveyancing firms, estate agents, or lenders — build on PDTF. It's the data standard your agents need.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
